hands_on_practices.solution:
1. For an isentropic calorically-perfect gas mixture the stagnation-to-static temperature ratio is
$$\frac{T_0}{T}=1+\frac{\gamma_{\text{mix}}-1}{2}M^2.$$
2. The mass-specific heats of each constituent are
$$c_{p,i}=\frac{\gamma_i}{\gamma_i-1}\frac{R_u}{M_i},\quad
c_{v,i}=\frac{1}{\gamma_i-1}\frac{R_u}{M_i},\quad i=1,2.$$
3. The mixture specific heats (mass basis) are
$$c_{p,\text{mix}}=c_1c_{p,1}+c_2c_{p,2}
=R_u\left(\frac{c_1\gamma_1}{(\gamma_1-1)M_1}+\frac{c_2\gamma_2}{(\gamma_2-1)M_2}\right),$$
$$c_{v,\text{mix}}=c_1c_{v,1}+c_2c_{v,2}
=R_u\left(\frac{c_1}{(\gamma_1-1)M_1}+\frac{c_2}{(\gamma_2-1)M_2}\right).$$
Hence
$$\gamma_{\text{mix}}=\frac{c_{p,\text{mix}}}{c_{v,\text{mix}}},\qquad
\gamma_{\text{mix}}-1=\frac{c_{p,\text{mix}}-c_{v,\text{mix}}}{c_{v,\text{mix}}}
=\frac{R_u\left(\frac{c_1}{M_1}+\frac{c_2}{M_2}\right)}{R_u\left(\frac{c_1}{(\gamma_1-1)M_1}+\frac{c_2}{(\gamma_2-1)M_2}\right)}
=\frac{\frac{c_1}{M_1}+\frac{c_2}{M_2}}{\frac{c_1}{(\gamma_1-1)M_1}+\frac{c_2}{(\gamma_2-1)M_2}}.$$
4. Substituting into the isentropic relation gives
$$\frac{T_0}{T}
=1+\frac{M^2}{2}\frac{\displaystyle\frac{c_1}{M_1}+\frac{c_2}{M_2}}
{\displaystyle\frac{c_1}{(\gamma_1-1)M_1}+\frac{c_2}{(\gamma_2-1)M_2}}.$$

We start from the isentropic bulk modulus definition 
$$K \;=\;\rho\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial\rho}\right)_s
\;=\;K_0 + n\,p
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\frac{dp}{d\rho}=\frac{K_0+n\,p}{\rho}.$$
Integrating from $(p,\rho)$ to $(p_0,\rho_0)$,
$$\int_{p}^{p_0}\frac{dp}{K_0+n\,p}
=\int_{\rho}^{\rho_0}\frac{d\rho}{\rho}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\ln\frac{\rho_0}{\rho}
=\frac{1}{n}\ln\frac{K_0+n\,p_0}{K_0+n\,p}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\frac{\rho_0}{\rho}
=\left[\frac{K_0+n\,p_0}{K_0+n\,p}\right]^{1/n}.$$
Next, the stagnation enthalpy relation for a barotropic fluid gives
$$h_0-h=\frac{u^2}{2}
\quad\text{with}\quad dh=\frac{dp}{\rho}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\int_{p}^{p_0}\frac{dp}{\rho}
=\frac{u^2}{2}.$$
Express $\rho$ as a function of $p$ along the isentrope:
$$\rho(p')=\frac{\rho}{(K_0+n\,p)^{1/n}}\,(K_0+n\,p')^{1/n},$$
so
$$\frac{1}{\rho(p')}
=\frac{(K_0+n\,p)^{1/n}}{\rho\,(K_0+n\,p')^{1/n}}.$$
Hence
$$\frac{u^2}{2}
=\frac{(K_0+n\,p)^{1/n}}{\rho}\,
\frac{1}{n-1}\left[(K_0+n\,p_0)^{\frac{n-1}{n}}-(K_0+n\,p)^{\frac{n-1}{n}}\right].
$$
Using $a^2=K/\rho=(K_0+n\,p)/\rho$ and 
$K_0+n\,p_0=\rho a^2(\rho_0/\rho)^n$, one finds after simplification
$$\frac{u^2}{2}
=\frac{a^2}{n-1}\left[\left(\frac{\rho_0}{\rho}\right)^{n-1}-1\right],
\quad M^2=\frac{u^2}{a^2}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
M^2=\frac{2}{n-1}\left[\left(\frac{\rho_0}{\rho}\right)^{n-1}-1\right].$$
Solving for $\rho_0/\rho$ gives
$$\left(\frac{\rho_0}{\rho}\right)^{n-1}
=1+\frac{n-1}{2}M^2
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\frac{\rho_0}{\rho}
=\left(1+\frac{n-1}{2}M^2\right)^{1/(n-1)}.$$
